In article <1993May7.184011.2202@qualcomm.com>, karn@unix.ka9q.ampr.org (Phil Karn) writes:
> What's to prevent super-encryption of the Law Enforcement block? That
> is, before sending the law enforcement block you encrypt it (e.g., in
> software) with your own cipher (and secret key). The recipient
> decrypts it and passes it onto the Clipper chip. All other ciphertext
> from Clipper goes direct.
> 
> This might be one way to use an existing Clipper chip for high speed
> encryption without leaving yourself open to the abuses of law enforcement.
> 
> Phil

Nothing at all. The only drawback is that it wont work when talking to
a device (say an ATT secure phone) that doesn't super-encrypt.

But if you're going to implement your own cipher in software, why have
the clipper at all.
